ce:section.ce:para:
The specific surface area and porous structure were probed off the samples by nitrogen adsorption–desorption isotherms. SiO2 NFMs and CQDs/g-C3N4@SiO2 NFMs showed type IV N2 adsorption–desorption isotherms with significant hysteresis lines, indicating their mesoporous structure (Fig. 3
                        ). The specific surface area of CQDs/g-C3N4@SiO2 NFMs (38.993 m2/g) was 1.85 times higher than that of SiO2 NFMs (21.075 m2/g) (Table 1
                        ). The large specific surface area confers more active sites, which facilitates mass transfer in surface reactions. In addition, with the in-situ growth of CQDs/g-C3N4, the pore volume and pore size increased from 0.0108 cm3/g and 2.998 nm to 0.1761 cm3/g and 19.008 nm, respectively, as the alkaline thermal etching of NH3. The porous structure facilitates the adsorption of pollutants and dramatically reduces the agglomeration and loss during photocatalysis.
